node.text:
It can be frustrating to watch the world pass you by feeling like you don’t have time to accomplish goals that others do. 

The real question isn’t whether you have time, but whether you spend time on the things that matter. 

I often hear “I don’t have hours to work out a day and it isn’t my job”. It wasn’t mine either. 

When I was 320 pounds I was in school, working through my teaching practicum, commuting an hour and a half each way daily, getting my advanced degree, working other jobs. I found time to prioritize my health. Nothing about my schedule eased up when I decided to get healthy. I watched less tv. Spent less time sitting. Spent less time binging. 
My priorities shifted. 
My health became top of the list and I found time that otherwise would have been devoted to distractions like TV or scrolling through my phone. 
I had to take a good hard look at myself and recognize that my problem wasn’t time. It was disinterest. 

For the first few years of my journey, I was teaching middle school English, running practices before and after school, working as a personal trainer after practices, and finding time for my own training goals every single day. 5 am - 11 pm. Every day. 

I’m not glorifying the “drive yourself into the ground” lifestyle. This isn’t some “Boss Babe” bullshit. We make time for the things that matter. Ditch the distraction. Ditch the excuses. Your schedule will clear right up. 

Not everyone’s circumstances are the same, but before you write this journey off as impossible, take a hard inventory of where you spend your time and ask yourself “am I really THAT BUSY... or am I scared to prioritize this?”

I was scared. 
To fail. 
To fight. 
To be uncomfortable. 

And then I wasn’t. I was excited. To become exactly who I wanted. To shape my future. To write my story. 

I didn’t want to feel like the world was full of other people achieving their dreams while I watched from the sidelines. I wanted to play. 

Put me in coach! I’m ready to play.

📸@jakegravesphotos

node.text:
Flashback to 2019: I was drowning in this video from May 2019. This isn’t easy to post. It’s an uncomfortable, dark part of myself that I always wanted to keep secret. But that’s what this is. Binging. Compulsive food restrictions. Purging. It’s secrets. I know I’m not alone in this. So hopefully, if you’re struggling, you know you’re not alone, too. ❤️

Secrets have no power when they are not secret. 

 I have a vivid memory of making this video in May 2019, grasping for straws to try to pull myself out of my relapsed eating disorder. After years of being morbidly obese, I’d fallen madly in love with fitness and lost 130+lbs only to find that happiness didn’t magically arrive when the scale dropped. Instead, I found an obsessive need to get smaller and smaller... I’d thrown myself completely into bodybuilding, working with, training, and assisting the best trainers and bodybuilders in the world, and secretly sunken deeper and deeper into the shadows of myself, hiding food, refusing to eat, binging and purging, attempting to soothe my anxieties, fear of failure, feelings of inadequacy, and depression through my main coping mechanism - hyper-fixation on food (Eating all of it. Eating none of it. Compulsive tracking. Compulsive restricting - anything that felt like a semblance of control). 

I made these videos. I stayed present in binges instead of losing track of time and falling into a fugue state of food coma. I sought professional help and spoke out loud my darkest thoughts. I talked about my most secret shame publicly, giving light to my darkness. I formed a community of struggling women and men to do the same and lean on one another, finally realizing they weren’t alone in this. I worked at it. I still work at it. 

I’d never gone back and found this video until yesterday. 

I’ll leave this here in case it helps someone feel less alone ❤️ You’re not alone. You’re not broken. Hang in there. Keep fighting.

node.text: Trying to be as open and vulnerable as possible here. Very wildly uncomfortable, but I wanted to walk you guys through the sensations, emotions, and frenetic energy that can come from a binge or urge to binge. In this video I walk you through a live play-by-play of a binge eating trigger and offer my own methods for getting through it.

node.title: Live Play by Play of a Binging Trigger

node.text:
Hello Giants ❤️ My apologies that this live starts off so frenetic. I wasn’t anticipating posting this, but so many amazing things came up in this chat. And I want you guys to have access to them. Fast forward through the first few minutes - I’m being annoying and all over the place. But then get out your pen and paper. I promise the rest of this episode is filled with useful information that can help you re-center and refocus.  It’s time to actively start pursuing the life that you love.

If you’re struggling with finding motivation, loving yourself, building a life you actually enjoy, or understanding a bit about fitness (or you’re curious about the next few steps for my journey) this live is for you! 

I truly love and adore you guys and appreciate your support more than you could possibly know. 

I hope that the teacher in me is bringing even just a little bit of information from my own story and the stories of others to help you build a life you truly love!

LIVE GIANT ❤️
Laura

My favorite snack thinks your a snack, too! @thatsit found out I’m a huge fan of all of their healthy, mouth watering treats and now they want to gift a bunch of their products to you! It’s time to find freedom around your food - no guilt, no shame, no secrets. 

🎁8 pouches of truffles to each winner
Four pouches (banana, date, raisin, fig) for you and four pouches for your Valentine!

To enter

Open to USA! Winners will be announced February 8th by 11:59pm.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by LAURA MICETICH | Coach⬇️130+lb in Los Angeles, California with @jmihalyfit, and @drjosephmichaels. May be an image of 1 person and standing.

node.text:
August 30th - 23 days away ✂️

Arms. Upper back. Lower body. ✌️peace out. 🪡 

@drjosephmichaels you ready? 

Mental check in:

No filters. On the photo. On the thoughts. 

So. We’re at that point where the upper limit fear kicks in. 
Less than a month away from skin removal (for context, I had my tummy tuck in 2018 when sharing all of this scared the SHIT out of me. Now my vulnerability and self expression is non- negotiable, so talking about this is wayyyy easier)

I’ve never been here. 
Never been this lean while eating a proper amount of food and not relapsing into disordered patterns.
Never been this focused on self growth without it being a shield for emptiness. 
Never been so sure that everything happens for a reason and we all have the capacity for magic resting untapped below the surface. 
It’s almost scarier than everything imploding. 

I can feel myself teetering on a new edge. Of training. Of physique. Of my company. Of my self work. Of my journey. ⛰ 

And trust me. 
It’s scaring the shit out of me. 
In the best way. 
In the big, gut check, tingle in my toes kind of way. 

It’s terrifying to know you’ve never tread on this ground… that where you stand is firm and comfortable and safe. 
And you’re going to willingly step beyond it. 

That the excuses you made… the “I’m not built for that”, “I’m not that type of girl”, “I could never”… aren’t real. That they are simply safety nets you put in place to protect yourself… from pain. From disappoint. From heart ache. From failure. And that you made them up. ❤️

That’s scary. And it should be. 

So I’m going to champion you here. 
You are incredible. 
You are capable. 
You are ready. 

I get how scary that edge is. 
Leaving your comfort zone. 
Leaving your excuses. 
Leaving the zone of good enough for the zone of untapped excellence. 

But if even a tiny voice in your head says you can do it, do it. Fight like hell to keep that hand steady… to keep your foot firmly on the gas pedal toward your dreams… to break through the edge of comfort… the upper limit. ❤️

node.text:
Start over. Every single day. If you miss a day or have a bad workout, eat a candy bar, or even the entire candy store... wake up and start over. You didn’t fail. You don’t fail unless you quit. Even if you think it’s over, you might not be done. Stand back up and start over. You’re not starting from zero. You’re starting from experience. Stand up. Start over. 

Public service announcement from someone who has been there (320+lbs):

❌ there isn’t a shake that can replace a meal made from whole foods 
❌ there isn’t a pill that you can take that will help you lose weight (you actually have to eat less)
❌ someone selling a product doesn’t qualify them to give you nutrition advice (I’d suggest running the opposite direction) 
❌ even if you do keto, you still need to weigh and track your food (even too much protein can kick you out of ketosis. And calories in calories out is still the focus)
❌ you don’t need to cut out food groups from your daily intake to lose weight
❌ you shouldn’t just take advice from Netflix or blogs or personal experiences. 
❌ you don’t have to limit WHEN you eat to lose weight (calories don’t quadruple after 6pm)
❌ you don’t poop out excess calories (but if you could, y’all better believe I’d know about it)
❌ over consuming any macronutrient from ANY source (organic, watered with holy water, grown by virgins....doesn’t matter - once you hit your metabolic max, ALL THE REST IS STORED AS BODY FAT) Caloric surplus matters. 
❌ you can’t out work your food choices 
❌ the people who are most successful with long term weight maintenance pay attention to what they consume (either by tracking it or having some level of accountability to it) and
❌ There. Is. No. Quick. Fix.

node.text:
Pre-Surgery Physique Update: 5 weeks out 

5 weeks out from having the loose skin on my back, arms, and lower body removed with @drjosephmichaels (who did my tummy tuck in 2018. If I could do that first experience over, the only thing I would have changed was the level of transparency I had around the process. I was so scared to lose followers, support, approval… that I showed it. But not all of it.

Life gives us chances to learn. So this time, I’m doing it differently. 

This time around, I’m not scared… of the surgery or of the opinions of others and that’s on #growth ❤️

Full transparency. Every step of the way. The prep before. The process of the surgery. The highs and inevitable lows of recovery. And getting back into the swing of things post-recovery. 

No holds barred.

The goal over the next 5 weeks is to lean out in as healthy a mental and physical way possible while maintaining muscle mass to give @drjosephmichaels the best canvas to work with. If you’re new to this update, a couple weeks ago Dr. Michaels called to let me know the surgery we had scheduled for March 2022 could happen August 30th if I felt ready. And my answer was fuck yeah. So here we are. 

This is the leanest I’ve ever been. We’ve done everything before this week sitting at around 1900 calories. @jmihalyfit is helping me dial the fuck in as always. Plate is full. Heart is full. And all is possible ❤️✌️

Thank you for all the support and feel free to ask any questions. 

Love you guys

node.text:
Women of the world, hear me now. Recognize this. Preach this. Own this. 

You are not intimidating. 
They are intimidated. 

You don’t take up too much space. 
They are used to people playing small. 

Your inner light is not too bright. 
They are just used to dimming their own.

You are not mean or aggressive. 
You are honest and assertive. 

You do not make them uncomfortable. 
Your presence challenges their comfort. 

Do not be less so that they feel better about themselves. Do not play small to appease them. 

Own your truth. With kindness. And compassion. And understanding. But never with fear. Or hesitation. Or inauthenticity. 

Own your space.
Own your power. 
Own your story. 

Audio by: (not shown on Tiktok - @mariamilavazquez) 

#selflove #bodyacceptance #lawofattraction #unapologeticauthenticy
